3
00:02:24.066 --> 00:02:26.476 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Hi, I'm Jack Greasley.

4
00:02:26.546 --> 00:02:27.996 A:middle
I work for The Foundry.

5
00:02:28.446 --> 00:02:32.506 A:middle
And we make software to
do that sort of stuff.

6
00:02:32.506 --> 00:02:33.326 A:middle
It's a pretty cool job.

7
00:02:34.286 --> 00:02:37.906 A:middle
The Foundry was started about
15 years ago by two guys,

8
00:02:38.566 --> 00:02:42.256 A:middle
Bruno and Simon, working out
off a basement in Soho, London.

9
00:02:43.066 --> 00:02:45.216 A:middle
And they were making
image processing tools

10
00:02:45.216 --> 00:02:48.276 A:middle
for the local film and
visual effects industry.

11
00:02:49.216 --> 00:02:50.716 A:middle
Since then, we've grown a bit.

12
00:02:51.326 --> 00:02:56.066 A:middle
And we've really made a name
for ourselves by taking tools

13
00:02:56.066 --> 00:03:00.176 A:middle
and technologies out of
visual effects companies,

14
00:03:00.686 --> 00:03:03.916 A:middle
out of animation companies,
and commercializing them

15
00:03:03.916 --> 00:03:07.076 A:middle
and making them available
to everybody, so with tools

16
00:03:07.076 --> 00:03:10.416 A:middle
like NUKE from Digital
Domain and KATANA

17
00:03:11.036 --> 00:03:12.646 A:middle
from Sony Pictures Imageworks.

18
00:03:13.266 --> 00:03:15.206 A:middle
We've taken tools
and technologies

19
00:03:15.206 --> 00:03:18.716 A:middle
which were really only
available to the elite few

20
00:03:19.116 --> 00:03:21.216 A:middle
and made them available
to everybody.

21
00:03:22.106 --> 00:03:23.066 A:middle
One of the tools that we've done

22
00:03:23.066 --> 00:03:25.746 A:middle
that way is my particular
baby which is MARI.

23
00:03:26.606 --> 00:03:32.466 A:middle
And MARI is a GPU-accelerated
3D digital painting system.

24
00:03:32.946 --> 00:03:36.316 A:middle
And it was originally developed
at Weta Digital in New Zealand

25
00:03:36.936 --> 00:03:39.126 A:middle
which is Peter Jackson's
visual effects company.

26
00:03:40.516 --> 00:03:41.966 A:middle
I'm the product manager for MARI

27
00:03:41.966 --> 00:03:44.116 A:middle
but I'm also the
original author.

28
00:03:44.116 --> 00:03:46.586 A:middle
And what I'd like to
do is just take you

29
00:03:46.586 --> 00:03:50.356 A:middle
through just exactly what a
3D digital painting system

30
00:03:50.356 --> 00:03:53.196 A:middle
actually is.

31
00:03:53.436 --> 00:03:56.586 A:middle
When you're making a movie
and you're making a character

32
00:03:56.666 --> 00:04:01.716 A:middle
like Gollum here, he starts
off as a model, as a mesh.

33
00:04:01.966 --> 00:04:04.766 A:middle
And that model gives
you the overall shape.

34
00:04:04.766 --> 00:04:06.776 A:middle
It gives you the muscle
and the size of the object.

35
00:04:07.446 --> 00:04:11.316 A:middle
But it lacks the fine-grain
detail on the surface

36
00:04:11.316 --> 00:04:13.116 A:middle
that really make an
object compelling.

37
00:04:13.956 --> 00:04:18.766 A:middle
And it's the job of a texture
artist to go in there literally

38
00:04:18.766 --> 00:04:21.606 A:middle
with a brush and paint
in individual freckles,

39
00:04:21.606 --> 00:04:24.366 A:middle
individual veins, and
put the detail in there

40
00:04:24.366 --> 00:04:27.476 A:middle
that really makes it, you know,
go from a gray blank model

41
00:04:27.476 --> 00:04:29.706 A:middle
like this to something
looking pretty good.

42
00:04:30.726 --> 00:04:33.876 A:middle
And if any of you guys have
ever painted any figurines

43
00:04:33.876 --> 00:04:37.266 A:middle
or any models, you know just
how long it can take to get

44
00:04:37.266 --> 00:04:39.546 A:middle
that looking good and how much
detail you have to put in there.

45
00:04:40.206 --> 00:04:44.736 A:middle
So imagine that your model is
30-feet wide and it's going

46
00:04:44.736 --> 00:04:46.926 A:middle
to be projected on
a screen this size.

47
00:04:48.196 --> 00:04:52.176 A:middle
And this is the problem that
Weta Digital were facing.

48
00:04:52.716 --> 00:04:55.346 A:middle
How do you put enough
detail into your models

49
00:04:55.816 --> 00:04:58.336 A:middle
where the director can choose
to zoom into any part of it

50
00:04:58.336 --> 00:05:00.006 A:middle
and have it full screen?

51
00:05:00.996 --> 00:05:05.286 A:middle
In a game, you might put,
you know, one or two textures

52
00:05:05.286 --> 00:05:08.976 A:middle
on a character, and they
might be 1,000 pixel square

53
00:05:08.976 --> 00:05:10.686 A:middle
or 2,000 pixel square.

54
00:05:11.396 --> 00:05:13.406 A:middle
To get the level of
detail that they needed,

55
00:05:13.406 --> 00:05:17.636 A:middle
Weta Digital would often put
a patchwork of 500 textures

56
00:05:18.006 --> 00:05:19.696 A:middle
over the surface of
a single character.

57
00:05:20.536 --> 00:05:23.456 A:middle
And each of those
textures would be big.

58
00:05:23.456 --> 00:05:25.496 A:middle
It would be at least
2,000 pixel square

59
00:05:25.496 --> 00:05:27.396 A:middle
and sometimes much, much bigger.

60
00:05:28.666 --> 00:05:30.216 A:middle
And it doesn't stop there.

61
00:05:31.056 --> 00:05:34.286 A:middle
Those 500 textures only tell
you one thing about the surface.

62
00:05:34.656 --> 00:05:37.316 A:middle
They only tell you what color
it is, but you also need

63
00:05:37.316 --> 00:05:40.256 A:middle
to tell the system how bumpy
it is, how shiny it is,

64
00:05:40.306 --> 00:05:41.996 A:middle
how scratchy, how
dirty, how dusty.

65
00:05:42.576 --> 00:05:43.766 A:middle
And each one of those pieces

66
00:05:43.766 --> 00:05:46.356 A:middle
of information gives you
another 500 textures.

67
00:05:47.026 --> 00:05:51.886 A:middle
So very quickly you can be
up at 10,000 huge textures

68
00:05:52.286 --> 00:05:55.436 A:middle
for a single character,
and that can be 20, 30,

69
00:05:55.436 --> 00:05:57.016 A:middle
40 gigabytes of information.

70
00:05:57.016 --> 00:05:59.296 A:middle
And this was slowing
people down.

71
00:05:59.296 --> 00:06:00.606 A:middle
This was slowing
the artists down.

72
00:06:00.896 --> 00:06:03.656 A:middle
The one thing that artists
love to do is paint.

73
00:06:04.606 --> 00:06:07.136 A:middle
Things that they hate doing
are copying data around,

74
00:06:07.136 --> 00:06:09.196 A:middle
renaming files and
managing complexity.

75
00:06:10.086 --> 00:06:12.676 A:middle
And so, this is really
where MARI comes in.

76
00:06:13.336 --> 00:06:17.986 A:middle
I was hired by Weta
Digital in 2006 to work

77
00:06:17.986 --> 00:06:21.126 A:middle
with their texture artists
to really come up with tools

78
00:06:21.126 --> 00:06:22.656 A:middle
and technologies
to get them back

79
00:06:22.876 --> 00:06:25.126 A:middle
to doing what they
love which is painting.

80
00:06:25.886 --> 00:06:29.146 A:middle
So I got on a plane from London
down to Wellington, New Zealand

81
00:06:29.716 --> 00:06:34.386 A:middle
and worked with the texture
artists while they were working

82
00:06:34.386 --> 00:06:38.296 A:middle
on this little movie for
James Cameron called Avatar.

83
00:06:38.296 --> 00:06:42.636 A:middle
So my team and I were sitting
next to a room of fifty kind

84
00:06:42.636 --> 00:06:44.916 A:middle
of busy, kind of
caffeinated texture artists

85
00:06:45.456 --> 00:06:47.406 A:middle
for about four years.

86
00:06:48.096 --> 00:06:51.636 A:middle
And it got to the point where we
were releasing MARI three times

87
00:06:51.636 --> 00:06:51.926 A:middle
a day.

88
00:06:52.626 --> 00:06:55.036 A:middle
We'd do a version in the morning
and then fix it at lunchtime

89
00:06:55.036 --> 00:06:56.336 A:middle
and then another one
in the afternoon.

90
00:06:57.236 --> 00:07:00.186 A:middle
And if releasing three times
a day wasn't, you know,

91
00:07:00.256 --> 00:07:02.636 A:middle
enough work, my brand
new girlfriend

92
00:07:02.636 --> 00:07:05.076 A:middle
at that time was a
texture artist using MARI.

93
00:07:06.496 --> 00:07:09.396 A:middle
It took me a little
while to work out how

94
00:07:09.396 --> 00:07:10.866 A:middle
to prioritize her bugs properly.

95
00:07:11.036 --> 00:07:13.036 A:middle
[ Laughter ]

96
00:07:13.056 --> 00:07:16.116 A:middle
But I'm glad to say it worked
out and we're still together.

97
00:07:17.111 --> 00:07:19.111 A:middle
[ Applause ]

98
00:07:19.206 --> 00:07:19.546 A:middle
Thank you.

99
00:07:20.031 --> 00:07:22.031 A:middle
[ Applause ]

100
00:07:22.046 --> 00:07:24.776 A:middle
So MARI was incredibly
successful at Weta.

101
00:07:24.776 --> 00:07:29.036 A:middle
Every tool-- so every model,
every character, every plant,

102
00:07:29.656 --> 00:07:32.576 A:middle
everything that Weta Digital
painted for Avatar was done

103
00:07:32.576 --> 00:07:35.246 A:middle
in MARI, and that was
several thousand assets.

104
00:07:36.066 --> 00:07:38.616 A:middle
Avatar did OK as well.

105
00:07:38.616 --> 00:07:41.796 A:middle
You know, I think three billion
dollars at the Box Office.

106
00:07:42.576 --> 00:07:46.106 A:middle
And MARI continues to be used
at Weta Digital until today.

107
00:07:46.396 --> 00:07:47.676 A:middle
Every movie that
they've released

108
00:07:47.676 --> 00:07:50.796 A:middle
since 2008 has used
MARI as its--

109
00:07:50.796 --> 00:07:51.786 A:middle
as their main texture tool.

110
00:07:52.386 --> 00:07:56.086 A:middle
So this includes things like
The Avengers, The Adventures

111
00:07:56.086 --> 00:07:59.106 A:middle
of Tintin, Rise of the Planet
of the Apes, and most recently,

112
00:07:59.596 --> 00:08:03.126 A:middle
this guy, again, for The Hobbit.

113
00:08:03.316 --> 00:08:08.336 A:middle
In 2010, Weta Digital and The
Foundry came to an agreement

114
00:08:08.336 --> 00:08:09.266 A:middle
to commercialize MARI.

115
00:08:09.976 --> 00:08:12.936 A:middle
So The Foundry licensed
MARI from Weta.

116
00:08:12.936 --> 00:08:15.646 A:middle
But what that really
meant is that they sold it

117
00:08:15.646 --> 00:08:17.016 A:middle
and they sold me along with it.

118
00:08:17.016 --> 00:08:21.676 A:middle
So I got on a plane from
Wellington, New Zealand back

119
00:08:21.676 --> 00:08:24.306 A:middle
to London which is 32
hours door-to-door.

120
00:08:24.986 --> 00:08:27.306 A:middle
And this time, I was
coming back with a USB stick

121
00:08:27.306 --> 00:08:33.405 A:middle
for the source code and an
invoice for The Foundry to sign.

122
00:08:33.405 --> 00:08:35.756 A:middle
My role at The Foundry
was simple.

123
00:08:36.405 --> 00:08:38.866 A:middle
We wanted to make MARI
the industry standard

124
00:08:39.466 --> 00:08:41.926 A:middle
for visual effects,
3D digital painting.

125
00:08:42.416 --> 00:08:46.586 A:middle
Over the last three
years, we've done that.

126
00:08:46.636 --> 00:08:48.826 A:middle
We've been incredibly successful
to the point that nine

127
00:08:48.826 --> 00:08:50.526 A:middle
out of ten of the
movies nominated

128
00:08:50.526 --> 00:08:53.176 A:middle
for visual effects
Oscars this year used MARI

129
00:08:53.176 --> 00:08:54.866 A:middle
as their main texture
painting system.

130
00:08:55.696 --> 00:08:57.326 A:middle
The only reason that
the tenth didn't is

131
00:08:57.326 --> 00:08:59.426 A:middle
that they didn't buy it in time
enough to use on the movie.

132
00:09:01.056 --> 00:09:03.936 A:middle
MARI is at use-- in
use at a whole bunch

133
00:09:03.936 --> 00:09:05.056 A:middle
of companies you
will have heard of,

134
00:09:05.056 --> 00:09:07.756 A:middle
so there's Industrial Light
&amp; Magic over in the Presidio,

135
00:09:08.176 --> 00:09:10.616 A:middle
DreamWorks Animations,
Sony Pictures Imageworks.

136
00:09:11.256 --> 00:09:13.526 A:middle
So really if you've seen a movie
over the last couple of years

137
00:09:13.526 --> 00:09:16.656 A:middle
in which there has been an
alien, a spaceship, a monster,

138
00:09:16.656 --> 00:09:19.006 A:middle
something blowing up,
you've seen MARI at work.

139
00:09:19.006 --> 00:09:22.756 A:middle
One of the really
great things though

140
00:09:22.756 --> 00:09:25.566 A:middle
about taking an in-house
tool something thats design

141
00:09:25.566 --> 00:09:29.216 A:middle
for one specific task and making
it available to everybody is

142
00:09:29.216 --> 00:09:33.416 A:middle
that you start seeing uses
that you never expected for it.

143
00:09:33.416 --> 00:09:36.166 A:middle
We've seen it cropping up
in games, in architecture,

144
00:09:36.166 --> 00:09:38.906 A:middle
in digital design, and even
in amazing artwork like this

145
00:09:38.906 --> 00:09:40.296 A:middle
which is from an album cover.

146
00:09:41.436 --> 00:09:45.846 A:middle
One of our most technically
innovative artists is a good

147
00:09:45.846 --> 00:09:47.816 A:middle
friend of mine called Scott
Metzger who works out of LA.

148
00:09:47.816 --> 00:09:51.466 A:middle
And he's coming up with
new novel techniques

149
00:09:51.526 --> 00:09:54.206 A:middle
for capturing digital
environments

150
00:09:54.206 --> 00:09:58.226 A:middle
and making photorealistic
rendering incredibly easy to do.

151
00:09:59.176 --> 00:10:01.656 A:middle
So what this really means is
Scott went out one weekend

152
00:10:01.656 --> 00:10:04.116 A:middle
and rented an industrial
laser scanner

153
00:10:04.366 --> 00:10:07.176 A:middle
and started scanning things,
and he scanned his apartment.

154
00:10:08.086 --> 00:10:11.106 A:middle
And he scanned it down
to millimeter accuracy.

155
00:10:11.866 --> 00:10:15.396 A:middle
And ran around his apartment
with a camera taking hundreds

156
00:10:15.396 --> 00:10:19.166 A:middle
and hundreds of reference
photographs making this enormous

157
00:10:19.206 --> 00:10:23.146 A:middle
dataset which he pulled
into MARI and used MARI

158
00:10:23.306 --> 00:10:24.986 A:middle
to paint those photos down onto

159
00:10:24.986 --> 00:10:26.686 A:middle
to this enormous
scan that he made.

160
00:10:27.226 --> 00:10:30.296 A:middle
And this created-- I think
it was a 20 gigabyte dataset

161
00:10:30.866 --> 00:10:33.106 A:middle
that he was able to
fly around inside

162
00:10:33.106 --> 00:10:34.716 A:middle
of MARI, edit in real time.

163
00:10:35.416 --> 00:10:40.466 A:middle
But it also meant that he could
make amazing photorealistic

164
00:10:40.466 --> 00:10:41.656 A:middle
renderings like this.

165
00:10:42.216 --> 00:10:45.086 A:middle
You can actually zoom down
into the work surfaces

166
00:10:45.086 --> 00:10:46.186 A:middle
and you can see fingerprints,

167
00:10:46.186 --> 00:10:50.156 A:middle
you can see fine-grained
detail in the paint work.

168
00:10:51.216 --> 00:10:54.056 A:middle
And this is an incredibly
useful thing

169
00:10:54.056 --> 00:10:56.866 A:middle
for the visual effects
industry and the film industry

170
00:10:57.186 --> 00:10:58.226 A:middle
because when you're
making a film,

171
00:10:58.226 --> 00:11:01.756 A:middle
what you normally do
is you build a set,

172
00:11:02.446 --> 00:11:05.566 A:middle
you put some cameras on the set,
you get the actors on the set,

173
00:11:06.246 --> 00:11:09.736 A:middle
you film it, and then the set
gets torn down and thrown away.

174
00:11:09.736 --> 00:11:12.986 A:middle
But what often happens
is two months later,

175
00:11:12.986 --> 00:11:15.056 A:middle
the director has this
flash of inspiration

176
00:11:15.326 --> 00:11:17.036 A:middle
that the thing that's
really going

177
00:11:17.036 --> 00:11:21.006 A:middle
to give him the Oscar this
time is a zoom through this set

178
00:11:21.006 --> 00:11:23.926 A:middle
which is now sitting somewhere
in a dumpster in Hollywood.

179
00:11:24.796 --> 00:11:26.736 A:middle
And these are called
pickup shots,

180
00:11:26.736 --> 00:11:28.676 A:middle
and they're incredibly
expensive to do.

181
00:11:28.976 --> 00:11:31.516 A:middle
You need to go and find the
bits of set that still exists,

182
00:11:31.516 --> 00:11:32.636 A:middle
you need to rebuild the set,

183
00:11:32.636 --> 00:11:34.046 A:middle
you need to reconstruct
the lighting,

184
00:11:34.496 --> 00:11:35.946 A:middle
you need to match
everything perfectly.

185
00:11:36.716 --> 00:11:40.386 A:middle
But with this technique, you
can actually capture the set

186
00:11:40.386 --> 00:11:42.176 A:middle
and its entirety, all
of the information,

187
00:11:42.176 --> 00:11:44.216 A:middle
all the lighting,
when you're shooting.

188
00:11:44.586 --> 00:11:47.406 A:middle
And when the director has this
amazing flash of inspiration,

189
00:11:47.846 --> 00:11:50.786 A:middle
it's then incredibly cheap
to do pickup shots rather

190
00:11:50.786 --> 00:11:52.426 A:middle
than incredibly expensive.

191
00:11:53.936 --> 00:11:57.046 A:middle
All of the examples
that I've shown

192
00:11:57.046 --> 00:11:59.816 A:middle
up until now have been
running on Windows and Linux.

193
00:12:00.586 --> 00:12:03.636 A:middle
But MARI was originally
developed for the first couple

194
00:12:03.636 --> 00:12:07.286 A:middle
of years of its life on
both Macintosh and Linux.

195
00:12:07.866 --> 00:12:09.126 A:middle
Unfortunately, as I mentioned,

196
00:12:09.126 --> 00:12:11.276 A:middle
we were releasing
three times a day

197
00:12:11.816 --> 00:12:13.856 A:middle
and maintaining six builds a day

198
00:12:13.856 --> 00:12:16.036 A:middle
in full production was really
more than we could deal with.

199
00:12:16.666 --> 00:12:18.746 A:middle
So we concentrated
on Linux at the time,

200
00:12:18.746 --> 00:12:21.456 A:middle
but I'm incredibly pleased that
MARI is actually coming back

201
00:12:21.516 --> 00:12:23.126 A:middle
to the Mac later this summer.

202
00:12:23.266 --> 00:12:24.936 A:middle
Thank you.

203
00:12:25.516 --> 00:12:28.256 A:middle
[ Applause ]

204
00:12:28.756 --> 00:12:30.336 A:middle
We've been developing on

205
00:12:30.336 --> 00:12:33.376 A:middle
and targeting common
generation Mac hardware.

206
00:12:33.916 --> 00:12:35.796 A:middle
And partially this
is really selfish.

207
00:12:35.796 --> 00:12:38.556 A:middle
I want to demo on my brand new
shiny retina Macbook Pro and not

208
00:12:38.556 --> 00:12:42.406 A:middle
on a big ugly laptop
I've got at the moment.

209
00:12:43.036 --> 00:12:48.026 A:middle
The porting process for us has
been pretty straightforward.

210
00:12:48.856 --> 00:12:50.376 A:middle
It's really just
some housekeeping.

211
00:12:50.376 --> 00:12:52.426 A:middle
We need to take MARI's
OpenGL usage

212
00:12:52.426 --> 00:12:54.376 A:middle
because it really is
fully OpenGL based

213
00:12:54.886 --> 00:12:58.066 A:middle
and update it to
3.2 core profile.

214
00:12:58.756 --> 00:12:59.876 A:middle
This is something
we've been meaning

215
00:12:59.876 --> 00:13:00.866 A:middle
to do for a while anyway.

216
00:13:01.106 --> 00:13:03.476 A:middle
It really gives us a
lot of benefits in terms

217
00:13:03.476 --> 00:13:05.896 A:middle
of performance, speed,

218
00:13:05.896 --> 00:13:07.906 A:middle
simplicity of code
and stability.

219
00:13:08.806 --> 00:13:11.326 A:middle
And it's taken us
about six weeks to go

220
00:13:11.326 --> 00:13:13.976 A:middle
from absolutely nothing, MARI
didn't compile on the Mac,

221
00:13:13.976 --> 00:13:17.916 A:middle
didn't run on the Mac, to
being able to demo here today

222
00:13:17.916 --> 00:13:19.746 A:middle
which you guys will be
seeing in a few minutes.

223
00:13:20.786 --> 00:13:24.556 A:middle
The screenshots you can see
on the screen were taken

224
00:13:24.556 --> 00:13:26.466 A:middle
about a week apart
by my developers

225
00:13:26.466 --> 00:13:28.166 A:middle
as they were bringing MARI up.

226
00:13:28.956 --> 00:13:31.866 A:middle
The first image is the
first time MARI ran

227
00:13:31.866 --> 00:13:33.046 A:middle
on the Mac in five years.

228
00:13:33.736 --> 00:13:35.056 A:middle
The second one is a week later.

229
00:13:35.136 --> 00:13:36.456 A:middle
We have rendering
up and working.

230
00:13:37.036 --> 00:13:40.896 A:middle
And the third one is a week
after that where we're dealing

231
00:13:40.896 --> 00:13:45.936 A:middle
with big datasets we can
paint and we can animate.

232
00:13:46.526 --> 00:13:49.816 A:middle
So it really has been a
pretty seamless process.

233
00:13:49.936 --> 00:13:52.706 A:middle
However, we have been incredibly
lucky during this whole

234
00:13:52.706 --> 00:13:55.246 A:middle
process-- have been given
access to the new Mac Pro.

235
00:13:56.496 --> 00:14:00.886 A:middle
We originally designed MARI
with multiple GPUs in mind.

236
00:14:01.686 --> 00:14:05.486 A:middle
For me it makes so much sense
that you're going to want

237
00:14:05.486 --> 00:14:07.496 A:middle
to be processing
huge amounts of data

238
00:14:07.496 --> 00:14:09.886 A:middle
on one device while you're
displaying it fluidly

239
00:14:09.886 --> 00:14:12.396 A:middle
at 60 frames per
second on a second.

240
00:14:13.086 --> 00:14:16.896 A:middle
However, we've not really
ever seen a viable platform

241
00:14:16.896 --> 00:14:18.296 A:middle
for us to do this before.

242
00:14:18.856 --> 00:14:20.936 A:middle
We don't see multiple
GPUs installed

243
00:14:20.936 --> 00:14:22.556 A:middle
in visual effects
artist machines.

244
00:14:23.256 --> 00:14:25.696 A:middle
We see it in the
gaming world, you know,

245
00:14:25.696 --> 00:14:28.646 A:middle
people who put two GPUs
in their gaming rig

246
00:14:28.646 --> 00:14:31.686 A:middle
so they can play Gears
of War at 1080p 60 hertz.

247
00:14:32.316 --> 00:14:35.156 A:middle
But that power has never
been available to artists.

248
00:14:36.216 --> 00:14:40.036 A:middle
The multiple GPUs in the new
Mac Pro especially combined

249
00:14:40.036 --> 00:14:41.286 A:middle
with the updated OpenGL

250
00:14:41.286 --> 00:14:45.876 A:middle
and OpenCL support makes
it just a dream platform

251
00:14:45.876 --> 00:14:46.766 A:middle
for us to develop on it.

252
00:14:46.766 --> 00:14:49.996 A:middle
It's been really a
fantastic experience.

253
00:14:50.556 --> 00:14:53.316 A:middle
It's also going to make
my life a lot easier.

254
00:14:53.316 --> 00:14:56.786 A:middle
A large part of my job
is actually working

255
00:14:56.786 --> 00:15:00.356 A:middle
with our most demanding
customers to help them design

256
00:15:00.356 --> 00:15:04.246 A:middle
and build systems that
will meet their, you know,

257
00:15:04.726 --> 00:15:05.936 A:middle
incredible requirements.

258
00:15:05.936 --> 00:15:08.586 A:middle
I often get emails in the
morning along the lines of,

259
00:15:08.586 --> 00:15:11.376 A:middle
"So Jack, we tried to load
250 gigs of data into MARI

260
00:15:11.376 --> 00:15:12.616 A:middle
and it's running a
little bit slowly.

261
00:15:12.616 --> 00:15:13.396 A:middle
What can we do?"

262
00:15:14.856 --> 00:15:17.546 A:middle
So this machine is going to
make my life really easy.

263
00:15:17.686 --> 00:15:19.956 A:middle
I can say, "Go buy
the new Mac Pro."

264
00:15:20.516 --> 00:15:22.636 A:middle
[ Laughter ]

265
00:15:23.136 --> 00:15:27.686 A:middle
I can genuinely say it is the
best out-of-the-box experience

266
00:15:27.686 --> 00:15:29.446 A:middle
I've ever seen with MARI.

267
00:15:30.056 --> 00:15:34.626 A:middle
In terms of our most
demanding customers,

268
00:15:34.966 --> 00:15:39.916 A:middle
I think Pixar Animation Studios
are right up there with them.

269
00:15:40.086 --> 00:15:41.736 A:middle
I love working with
them as a company

270
00:15:41.736 --> 00:15:43.656 A:middle
because they represent
this amazing fusion

271
00:15:43.656 --> 00:15:44.986 A:middle
of being deeply artistic

272
00:15:44.986 --> 00:15:47.036 A:middle
but at the same time
being deeply technical.

273
00:15:48.336 --> 00:15:51.626 A:middle
Pixar were a very--
early adopter of MARI.

274
00:15:51.866 --> 00:15:55.166 A:middle
And we've been working with them
for the last, about three years,

275
00:15:55.616 --> 00:15:57.576 A:middle
to integrate MARI
into their pipeline

276
00:15:57.576 --> 00:16:00.196 A:middle
to put together new techniques

277
00:16:00.196 --> 00:16:02.836 A:middle
for creating incredibly
realistic characters

278
00:16:02.836 --> 00:16:04.156 A:middle
for their upcoming movies.

279
00:16:04.936 --> 00:16:08.316 A:middle
We're very lucky to have
Jonathan Hoffman here today

280
00:16:08.316 --> 00:16:10.796 A:middle
who's a shading technical
artist from Pixar.

281
00:16:12.086 --> 00:16:14.116 A:middle
Using MARI on the new Mac Pro,

282
00:16:14.116 --> 00:16:16.886 A:middle
he's going to be giving us a
sneak peak behind the scenes

283
00:16:17.386 --> 00:16:21.156 A:middle
into the process of how Pixar
design and build the characters

284
00:16:21.156 --> 00:16:22.256 A:middle
that are going to their movies.

285
00:16:22.676 --> 00:16:25.076 A:middle
But before we do that, I think
we should have a quick look

286
00:16:25.076 --> 00:16:27.126 A:middle
at some of the amazing work
that they've been up to

287
00:16:27.126 --> 00:16:28.176 A:middle
for the last couple of years.

288
00:16:29.516 --> 00:16:36.516 A:middle
[ Applause ]

289
00:16:37.016 --> 00:16:44.000 A:middle
[ Music ]

290
00:16:44.306 --> 00:16:46.196 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Tonight we party
like scarers!

291
00:16:46.196 --> 00:16:47.966 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I want to piece
of that action.

292
00:16:50.316 --> 00:16:51.466 A:middle
&gt;&gt; My friends call me Sully.

293
00:16:51.566 --> 00:16:52.186 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Mike Wazowski.

294
00:16:53.086 --> 00:16:55.816 A:middle
I'm officially a
college student.

295
00:16:56.736 --> 00:16:56.803 A:middle
Yeah!

296
00:16:58.136 --> 00:16:59.976 A:middle
&gt;&gt; We don't need to study
scaring, you know, do it.

297
00:17:00.126 --> 00:17:00.836 A:middle
&gt;&gt; That is a good point.

298
00:17:03.056 --> 00:17:04.886 A:middle
&gt;&gt; What's so scary about
a little librarian?

299
00:17:05.086 --> 00:17:06.776 A:middle
&gt;&gt; A bunch of guys went
to the hospital last year.

300
00:17:07.516 --> 00:17:08.616 A:middle
&gt;&gt; You can totally die.

301
00:17:09.236 --> 00:17:09.705 A:middle
&gt;&gt; And it's worth it.

302
00:17:12.126 --> 00:17:12.816 A:middle
Let the animal out!

303
00:17:14.066 --> 00:17:14.776 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Is that legal?

304
00:17:16.496 --> 00:17:18.506 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I've never seen him
this way in my life!

305
00:17:20.236 --> 00:17:22.336 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Trust me when I say
you are not going to want

306
00:17:22.536 --> 00:17:23.455 A:middle
to touch this bad boy.

307
00:17:23.455 --> 00:17:23.976 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I want to touch it.

308
00:17:26.626 --> 00:17:27.756 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Yeah, I want to touch him.

309
00:17:27.996 --> 00:17:29.336 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Hey, what are
you doing up there?

310
00:17:29.336 --> 00:17:31.516 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I can't go back to jail.

311
00:17:35.046 --> 00:17:35.836 A:middle
&gt;&gt; I'm going to rule!

312
00:17:40.516 --> 00:17:45.056 A:middle
[ Applause ]

313
00:17:45.556 --> 00:17:48.566 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Obviously a lot of work goes
into every one of our films.

314
00:17:48.566 --> 00:17:51.686 A:middle
It's truly a collaborative
effort between hundreds

315
00:17:52.126 --> 00:17:53.356 A:middle
of really talented people.

316
00:17:53.756 --> 00:17:54.436 A:middle
What I'm going to talk to you

317
00:17:54.436 --> 00:17:57.896 A:middle
about today is really only one
small part of the whole process.

318
00:17:59.296 --> 00:18:00.466 A:middle
You saw on the trailer,
there are a lot

319
00:18:00.466 --> 00:18:02.946 A:middle
of different characters
in this upcoming film

320
00:18:03.006 --> 00:18:06.066 A:middle
and each character presents its
own unique set of challenges.

321
00:18:06.646 --> 00:18:08.716 A:middle
With Monsters University,

322
00:18:08.826 --> 00:18:10.836 A:middle
obviously since this is a
prequel, we're going back

323
00:18:11.026 --> 00:18:12.896 A:middle
to the world of Monsters Inc.

324
00:18:13.036 --> 00:18:14.936 A:middle
which we haven't
been to since 2001.

325
00:18:15.556 --> 00:18:20.676 A:middle
And recreating that world, you
know, we wanted to stay true

326
00:18:20.676 --> 00:18:24.066 A:middle
to the essence of the design
while still pushing the limits

327
00:18:24.066 --> 00:18:26.516 A:middle
of what we can do
now that it's 2013.

328
00:18:26.626 --> 00:18:28.856 A:middle
Obviously the technology has
come a long way since then.

329
00:18:29.236 --> 00:18:30.926 A:middle
Our two primary characters

330
00:18:30.926 --> 00:18:34.296 A:middle
in this film are still Mike
Wazowski and James Sullivan

331
00:18:34.296 --> 00:18:35.356 A:middle
from Monsters Incorporated.

332
00:18:36.136 --> 00:18:38.636 A:middle
Now, since this is
their college days,

333
00:18:38.636 --> 00:18:40.486 A:middle
we needed to redesign
the characters to look

334
00:18:40.486 --> 00:18:42.826 A:middle
like teenagers, and that
might be more difficult

335
00:18:42.826 --> 00:18:46.286 A:middle
than you would think because how
exactly does one make a walking

336
00:18:46.286 --> 00:18:49.436 A:middle
eyeball look younger, right?

337
00:18:49.726 --> 00:18:51.856 A:middle
You don't normally think
about this sort of thing.

338
00:18:51.856 --> 00:18:55.436 A:middle
But the people in the art team
did an amazing job in figuring

339
00:18:55.436 --> 00:18:58.186 A:middle
out and envisioning, you know,
how you take these monsters

340
00:18:58.186 --> 00:18:59.086 A:middle
and make them look younger.

341
00:18:59.416 --> 00:19:02.376 A:middle
With Mike Wazowski, this image
by our production designer,

342
00:19:02.376 --> 00:19:05.296 A:middle
Ricky, is this great
progression of Mike all the way

343
00:19:05.296 --> 00:19:06.956 A:middle
from toddler to adulthood.

344
00:19:07.586 --> 00:19:10.366 A:middle
And this is the final design
for both of the main characters.

345
00:19:11.036 --> 00:19:12.836 A:middle
And there's a lot of
real subtle things here.

346
00:19:12.836 --> 00:19:14.696 A:middle
I'm going to kind of show you
some of the things that they did

347
00:19:14.696 --> 00:19:15.696 A:middle
to make them look younger.

348
00:19:16.136 --> 00:19:20.476 A:middle
With Mike Wazowski, you know,
we took lots of pictures of all

349
00:19:20.476 --> 00:19:22.876 A:middle
of the people of the
studio and looked at them

350
00:19:23.186 --> 00:19:24.396 A:middle
when they were teenagers
and then looked

351
00:19:24.396 --> 00:19:25.276 A:middle
at their adult pictures.

352
00:19:25.666 --> 00:19:28.296 A:middle
And we learned a few things,
you know, besides, you know,

353
00:19:28.636 --> 00:19:30.546 A:middle
we all are, you know, little
bit less hair, you know,

354
00:19:30.546 --> 00:19:31.376 A:middle
some things like that.

355
00:19:31.746 --> 00:19:36.666 A:middle
But with teenagers, teenagers
reach their adult height way

356
00:19:36.666 --> 00:19:38.056 A:middle
before they really fill in.

357
00:19:38.056 --> 00:19:40.326 A:middle
And so with Mike, you'll
notice he's the same height

358
00:19:40.326 --> 00:19:40.986 A:middle
as he was before.

359
00:19:40.986 --> 00:19:42.216 A:middle
His limbs are the same length.

360
00:19:42.516 --> 00:19:44.226 A:middle
His hands and his feet
are the same size.

361
00:19:44.566 --> 00:19:45.746 A:middle
But he's a lot skinnier, right?

362
00:19:45.746 --> 00:19:46.556 A:middle
He's lanky.

363
00:19:46.556 --> 00:19:49.376 A:middle
And there's a lot
of other things too.

364
00:19:49.506 --> 00:19:53.536 A:middle
The colors are much more vibrant
and saturated to give them

365
00:19:53.536 --> 00:19:54.616 A:middle
that sort of youthful glow.

366
00:19:54.836 --> 00:19:57.446 A:middle
The horns are shorter
and more blunted because,

367
00:19:57.836 --> 00:20:00.946 A:middle
obviously as you get older,
your horns get longer.

368
00:20:01.826 --> 00:20:04.756 A:middle
And with Mike, you know,
you've got this great detail

369
00:20:04.806 --> 00:20:06.976 A:middle
of that retainer just coming
out of high school, you know.

370
00:20:06.976 --> 00:20:08.386 A:middle
I'm sure a lot of you
had to deal with that.

371
00:20:08.926 --> 00:20:10.486 A:middle
And then with Sullivan,

372
00:20:10.486 --> 00:20:14.996 A:middle
my favorite detail is he's
got this great bedhead look.

373
00:20:14.996 --> 00:20:17.536 A:middle
But since it's all over his
body, it's his bed-body look.

374
00:20:17.536 --> 00:20:19.766 A:middle
It looks like he just
rolled out of bed and all

375
00:20:19.766 --> 00:20:20.676 A:middle
of his hair is disheveled.

376
00:20:21.816 --> 00:20:24.466 A:middle
So a lot of thought and
time and effort goes

377
00:20:24.466 --> 00:20:27.976 A:middle
into really making these
character designs perfect

378
00:20:28.136 --> 00:20:30.986 A:middle
for these characters,
to really stay true

379
00:20:30.986 --> 00:20:32.956 A:middle
to that original design
but really take them

380
00:20:32.956 --> 00:20:34.436 A:middle
in a new direction
for this film.

381
00:20:34.986 --> 00:20:38.646 A:middle
But for every main character,
for every, you know, for these--

382
00:20:38.686 --> 00:20:40.476 A:middle
our core characters,
we need a good foil,

383
00:20:40.476 --> 00:20:42.496 A:middle
we need a good antagonist
for the story.

384
00:20:42.496 --> 00:20:45.046 A:middle
And so, I'm going to
introduce you to the character

385
00:20:45.046 --> 00:20:47.096 A:middle
that I have the chance to work
on for this film and I'm going

386
00:20:47.096 --> 00:20:50.416 A:middle
to show you a never before
seen clip from the movie

387
00:20:50.416 --> 00:20:52.896 A:middle
to introduce that character.

388
00:20:53.786 --> 00:20:55.446 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Please, let me
try the simulator.

389
00:20:55.636 --> 00:20:56.416 A:middle
I'll surprise you.

390
00:20:57.156 --> 00:20:58.126 A:middle
&gt;&gt; Surprise me?

391
00:20:59.076 --> 00:21:01.096 A:middle
I doubt that very much.

392
00:21:03.236 --> 00:21:05.846 A:middle
&gt;&gt; All right, so that
is Dean Hardscrabble

393
00:21:05.846 --> 00:21:08.006 A:middle
of the Monsters University
School of Scaring.

394
00:21:08.376 --> 00:21:11.246 A:middle
Now, she is the scariest
monster on campus.

395
00:21:11.356 --> 00:21:13.166 A:middle
And she is a scaring legend.

396
00:21:13.856 --> 00:21:16.676 A:middle
And with a character like
this, where does it start?

397
00:21:16.786 --> 00:21:19.506 A:middle
How does a character go
from start to finish?

398
00:21:19.506 --> 00:21:20.316 A:middle
Where does it begin?

399
00:21:20.566 --> 00:21:22.356 A:middle
Well it starts with
a bunch of drawings.

400
00:21:22.866 --> 00:21:25.996 A:middle
The art team does hundreds
of drawings for weeks to try

401
00:21:25.996 --> 00:21:28.376 A:middle
and really figure out
what a character is,

402
00:21:28.476 --> 00:21:30.546 A:middle
to experiment with
different ideas.

403
00:21:31.126 --> 00:21:34.416 A:middle
And with Hardscrabble, they
had a very challenging goal.

404
00:21:34.416 --> 00:21:37.766 A:middle
They needed her to be
very poised and elegant

405
00:21:37.766 --> 00:21:39.376 A:middle
and have this sense
of authority.

406
00:21:39.906 --> 00:21:42.066 A:middle
But they also needed
her to be terrifying.

407
00:21:42.696 --> 00:21:44.976 A:middle
And they were trying a bunch of
different ideas but it wasn't

408
00:21:44.976 --> 00:21:49.656 A:middle
until they saw this video
of a Amazonian centipede

409
00:21:49.656 --> 00:21:51.216 A:middle
which these things are huge.

410
00:21:51.216 --> 00:21:52.776 A:middle
It's a giant Amazonian
centipede.

411
00:21:53.156 --> 00:21:57.466 A:middle
They saw this video and
it had this amazing grace

412
00:21:57.466 --> 00:21:59.386 A:middle
to it despite the fact
that the first things

413
00:21:59.386 --> 00:22:01.316 A:middle
that you see is "Wow,
that is scary.

414
00:22:01.316 --> 00:22:03.966 A:middle
I'm going to"-- you know, if you
see that you want to run away.

415
00:22:04.046 --> 00:22:07.746 A:middle
But you see it and it had this
movement, this deadly grace

416
00:22:07.746 --> 00:22:09.776 A:middle
to it, and that is
exactly what they wanted

417
00:22:09.776 --> 00:22:10.666 A:middle
for Dean Hardscrabble.

418
00:22:10.666 --> 00:22:13.546 A:middle
So the director, Dan Scanlon,
drew the centipede tail

419
00:22:13.546 --> 00:22:14.596 A:middle
onto the back of Hardscrabble

420
00:22:14.596 --> 00:22:16.196 A:middle
and they realized
that is the design.

421
00:22:16.636 --> 00:22:19.566 A:middle
That was the central
part of her visual look.

422
00:22:19.566 --> 00:22:23.926 A:middle
So this is the final design by
Jason Deamer and it really--

423
00:22:24.256 --> 00:22:27.296 A:middle
the central figure of the
design is that centipede,

424
00:22:27.296 --> 00:22:30.766 A:middle
but then he's incorporated all
these other really scary animals

425
00:22:30.856 --> 00:22:31.776 A:middle
into that design.

426
00:22:32.076 --> 00:22:35.276 A:middle
She's got these bat wings, the
sort of dragon/lizard head.

427
00:22:35.836 --> 00:22:39.226 A:middle
And this, you know,
this was the character

428
00:22:39.226 --> 00:22:42.186 A:middle
that they've been searching
for, this elegance and grace,

429
00:22:42.736 --> 00:22:46.456 A:middle
authority along with
this idea of being very,

430
00:22:46.456 --> 00:22:48.386 A:middle
very scary and terrifying.

431
00:22:49.556 --> 00:22:52.336 A:middle
The first film, we had a--

432
00:22:52.336 --> 00:22:55.376 A:middle
you know, we had this cast of
very candy colored characters,

433
00:22:55.446 --> 00:22:59.736 A:middle
these very bright, you know,
and saturated characters.

434
00:22:59.736 --> 00:23:02.696 A:middle
And with the next film, we
wanted to stay true to that.

435
00:23:03.266 --> 00:23:06.476 A:middle
But with Hardscrabble, we needed
to make sure that she still fit

436
00:23:06.476 --> 00:23:08.576 A:middle
in the world of all these
other characters and

437
00:23:08.576 --> 00:23:09.536 A:middle
yet was still scarier.

438
00:23:09.976 --> 00:23:12.126 A:middle
In Monsters Incorporated, if
you remember the character

439
00:23:12.166 --> 00:23:13.636 A:middle
of Waternoose, he was
a little bit different.

440
00:23:13.636 --> 00:23:16.016 A:middle
And so we were trying to go
for something similar to him

441
00:23:16.016 --> 00:23:18.486 A:middle
where he still fit in the
world but was different

442
00:23:18.486 --> 00:23:19.286 A:middle
than all the other characters.

443
00:23:19.286 --> 00:23:22.036 A:middle
She again needed to be
scarier and yet still feel

444
00:23:22.036 --> 00:23:23.176 A:middle
like she came from
the same planet.

445
00:23:24.406 --> 00:23:27.816 A:middle
So once the design is settled,
it really gets passed in to kind

